Can the Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time, the Swiss voters for a ban on building minarets and is widespread concern about the alleged Islamisation of Europe, John Bowen, an American academic, wrote a detailed report about whether Muslims can be integrated into one of the most pronounced säkularisiertesten societies of Europe - and be integrated.
Some readers will this new book from admiration for the work of the author: " why the French do not like the headscarf " (2006) , an elegant and that has divided and concerned the country for a decade and a half, and whose effects are still felt today.
The latest book by Mr Bowen has a broader perspective and more ambitious.
As a Good anthropologist, wants to know not only what the politicians and the media about Islam in France, but what is happening in the country.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now provide the 5-6 million Muslims in France what Mr Bowen calls " Islamic spaces ".
He is a good listener, he gives debates between teachers and students on the issues that concern them most.
Should A Muslim in a mosque or a town hall (or both) ?
Should be lectured young Muslims on The evolution and the rights of homosexuals?
A Muslim woman can marry a non - Muslim?
Is it permissible for A Muslim, to use a banking system based on interests to get a mortgage?
It is These seemingly mundane matters, he says, which are the daily life, rather than the political dramas concern the media.
The author identifies a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them, with the possible exception of Tariq Ramadan, a Muslim Arab born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how to be a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They do not push the debate until the end.
The Conservatives are suspicious about the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists that Mr Bowen interview tend to disagree with their counterparts from, supporters of Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia, who now have a small but influential presence among Muslims in Europe.
Bowen thinks that the Muslim values and the French secularism could be compatible.
But a compromise can be achieved with the efforts of each side.
He wondered how the French politicians (and the intellectual elite who fiercely defends secularism) are really committed to pluralism.
He Suggests that Muslims may be a rougher treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews who have also had to make their historic compromise with the secular republicanism.
Rather than a growing pragmatism, perceived an adjustment of values ".
Can the Islam be French? After reading this book, one tends to say " yes, but not yet. "
The trostloseste outlook of the world
The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatic than any other place on the planet.
The ice is melting at an alarming rate, taking with it a life that can survive elsewhere.
The interests of oil, gas, transport and fisheries have been approached in open waters, with diplomats, lawyers and now authors in their wake.
In " on thin ice " (" on thin ice ") Richard Ellis, a writer and illustrator, painted a natural history of the icon of the north, the polar bear.
Aware of the complicated history and politics of the whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers, which have proved themselves in the hunt for the polar bears.
The meeting of Admiral Nelson as a courageous cadete 14 years, fighting only with the end of his, is certainly a myth, but others are true.
The young, captured while following the bodies of their mothers just killed, were caught and sent to zoos and circuses.
A circus At the beginning of the 20th century, 75 polar bears at the same time.
Even today, the dimensions of a zoo are still typically a millionth part of the area of the scope of an adult wild. the climate is rarely mentioned: a polar bear living in Singapore was green because of algae that grow in his fur.
Click here for more information!
Ellis refers to the reports of other writers and historians and often to the threat posed by hunters on the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, the killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and Indians Inuits in powerful assault rifles, to express their prey.
Ironically, it is in the waters in the north of those two nations where the ice will last longer.
In his new book, " after the ice " (the ice " Alun Anderson, a former editor of New Scientist, offers a clear and the science of the Arctic and a fascinating glimpse of what may be the future there.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither the atmospheric scientists are still Ozeanografen can explain the speed of change.
It is not for lack of effort.
Travel pioneers of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th and early 20th century, for the first time, the melting of the ice.
Then The submarines in the Cold War the changing Grate the driving.
The satellite and the extensive series of probes in the icebergs are a useful supplement, but individuals resistant camped out in the cold.
Mr Anderson looks within the extraordinary, tiny world of supply system within the Arctic ice, formed by the nets of brackish water by freezing.
But, starting with the bear on the ice to the microscopic miracles in ice, all of them are threatened, once the summer ice, which is between 2013 and 2050.
