He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who had gathered on Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of the Arlington cemetery.
In 1992, Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, launched the event when he and others have decided to decorate several hundreds of graves in the cemetery in Arlington.
Now, to continue a tradition of 18 years, Morrill and his wife Karen, each year the trip, stopping in various cities along their way to organize the people in the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcester also founded a non - profit organization, Wreaths Across America (placed wreaths across America) , which has extended the event to other states.
This year more than 16,000 placed wreaths on the graves of the Arlington cemetery, around the Pentagon, on the graves of the cemetery Fayetteville National Cemetery enArkansas, in Battery Park in New York City and on the site of the memorial Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second consecutive year, the Walmart Foundation has donated more than $150,000 to buy and transport the crowns.
Charleen Hunt, 70, of Westminster, said that she had made the trip to Arlington in honour of her husband, a career soldier died.
While her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said that this is their way to give a reward to those who made sacrifices.
This is a small way in which civilians can support our troops, he said.
It is like visiting a family tomb.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, volunteers walked across the vast meadows and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers have chosen older graves dating from the First and second World war and the Vietnam War, because they are not as often as the new graves, the organisers.
The mood was cheerful, while children played and couples were taken by the hand, while the fresh pine branches to the grey of grave stones.
Each crown round was a dark green, with a small red ribbon tied at the top.
Near there, Section 60, where most veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried.
The United Service Organizations has given 1,000 kroner to decorate the section but the gloomy mood of the current wars invaded the area.
People wept openly, others prayed and families and friends kept each other in the cold air.
Some read aloud the names carved in stone, while others were inclined to see small black and white, information in the wetland for those whose tombstones have not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers in tears on the grave of her son.
