It will be a long time before another offer in Iraq.
Concerns about security, corroborated by massive coordinated bombings on Tuesday, and the political instability while the American military are withdrawn, probably prevented the American oil companies risk more forcefully in Iraq, which has the third largest crude oil in the world, said analysts.
US companies were in some cases at a disadvantage, because of their rivals, especially the Chinese and other energy companies controlled by the government, have significantly lower labor costs and are more prone to take risks because they are not accountable to shareholders.
Exxon - Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies to obtain contracts with the ministry.
Major U. S. companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which have deepened ties with the Iraqi Oil Ministry and have provided technical advice in recent years, are empty - handed.
The Russian company Lukoil and Gazprom were the main players in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The Chinese National Petroleum Corporation, owned by the state, in more contracts than any other companies and with large investments in contracts for two major fields.
We all know that China is on its way to becoming a major economic and technological power, said Assam Jihad, spokesman of the Ministry of Oil.
We are convinced that the Chinese company will be on a par with its competitors and will meet its commitments to Iraq.
Companies to submit proposals made offers which were then compared with the subsidy per barrel that the ministry was willing to pay to increase production above current levels for each field.
One of the main organizers of Al Qaeda in Pakistan
It is believed that a US missile which hit along the border with Afghanistan has killed one of the organizers of the operations this week, said on Friday, representatives of the counter - terrorism.
If confirmed, this would be the second deadly attack against a senior terrorist leader this autumn.
Saleh al-Somali was one of the two Arab men suspected to have been killed by a pair of missiles in their car, Tuesday, near the city of Miran Shah, in the province of North Waziristan, according to U. S. sources and Pakistani authorities in the region.
Local authorities said that the missiles were fired by an unmanned aircraft of the type operated by the CIA in the lawless tribal area of Pakistan.
They were driving a white car, in the direction of the Afghan border, when the car was hit, said an official of the civilian intelligence agency of Pakistan, speaking by telephone from Miran Shah.
The official said that local militants were rushed to the site and quickly seized what was left of the " completely destroyed ".
The local authorities were unable to verify the identities of the victims, but two representatives of the counter - terrorism Americans unspecified evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somali was described as a military planner of Al Qaeda, who led the operations of the terrorist group outside the region of Afghanistan - Pakistan.
He was involved in plots around the world, said a senior official, who wished to remain anonymous, citing the sensitive nature of the American air strikes inside Pakistani territory.
Given its central role, this probably included conspiracies of attacks against the United States and Europe.
He received instructions from the Topführern of Al Qaeda and translated into action plans for possible terrorist attacks.
The second US official said that Somali had risen rapidly in the ranks of al-Qaeda and had very good relations with other extremist groups in the region.
It may not be a household name for some Americans, but this does not diminish the threat it poses to us and our allies, said the second official.
If his death is confirmed, Somali would be the second leader of Al Qaeda or Taliban leader killed since September, when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, the leader of a militant group in the tribal area, and three other operators.
The pace of attacks carried out by CIA drones has declined since the summer, about six operations per month to two, according to the figures by the Long War Journal, a Web site run by a non - profit group.
The decline can be due to improved tactics of terrorist groups who have taken steps to reduce their vulnerability while ruthlessly to informants, said the site.
The UN special envoy in Kabul withdrew
The UN envoy in Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said on Friday that he would resign from his post in March, at the end a stormy tenure marred by allegations of widespread corruption in the presidential election supported by the UN.
The departure of Eide comes as the Obama administration has decided to send some 30,000 additional US troops to Afghanistan.
The UN envoy said that he supports the increase, but is concerned that the US timetable for military withdrawal that begins in 18 months to other NATO governments to withdraw its forces.
We need to accelerate the development of the Afghan security forces and send the right signal to the Afghans that they can trust the international community, Eide said in a telephone interview from Kabul.
Our commitment must be long term.
The Norwegian diplomat also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international civil servants helping the political transition in Afghanistan.
The increase in the military must be copied by civilians, he said.
Eide said that he was not resigning, but simply fulfilling a promise he made to his family in March 2008, only two years in Kabul.
He said that he wanted to prevent the United Nations.
Secretary - General Ban Ki - moon moon pass now, so that he had time to find a replacement.
What I have said is that it is better to start looking for a successor, said Eide.
When I came here, there was a gap of two months between the departure of my predecessor and my arrival.
Ban has begun to search for a replacement, According to UN officials.
The representatives say that the name of Staffan di Mistura was quoted; it is a citizen who recently addressed the UN mission in Baghdad, and Jean - Marie Guéhenno, a Frenchman who has previously led the peacekeeping missions.
Eide position in Afghanistan has been put to The test after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, accused in September, President Hamid Karzai in the presidential election in the country and to cover evidence of massive electoral fraud.
Eide denied the charges, but said that the allegations of Galbraith, who was fired, " have damaged the mission, because there was already a good dose of scepticism in relation to the international interference in the election ".
Eide said that he has recommended the appointment of a civilian representative to coordinate the rescue of US forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged the leadership of the UN to allow his successor to hire more staff from the United States and other Western countries that provided to the Afghan mission, saying that it would strengthen their confidence that their money is being used properly.
Eide expressed his frustration about the limits of its powers in Afghanistan, saying that the heavy regulations of the UN undermine their ability to attract talent.
The rules of the UN are such that I could not recruit only one person since May, he said.
This is catastrophic and must not continue.
Gates: Iran must undergo additional sanctions
The Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates said Friday that the world powers will soon be " significant additional sanctions " on Iran because of its failure to engage in talks on its nuclear ambitions.
Gates, speaking to a group of about 300 American soldiers in northern Iraq, during a trip to a week in war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq, the prospect of military action against the Islamic Republic.
There are no good options in Iran, he said, in response to the question of a soldier on the likelihood of such an event.
One of the things that I regret is that, if we have learned anything from Iraq over the past six years, it is the inherent unpredictability of the war.
The Obama administration is considering a package of sanctions against the military and political elite in Iran, but Gates has announced that some sanctions could also affect the Iranians in the street.
He said that a package of incentives and punishments " might be necessary to persuade the Iranian government that it is in reality less protected with nuclear weapons ", because " their people will suffer greatly " sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement from the White House spokesman, Robert Gibbs, the administration has joined the European leaders in warning that Iran will face consequences " credible " if its nuclear programme in full compliance with the UN Security Council and its supervisory body, the International Atomic Energy Agency.
Iran insists that it wants to develop nuclear knowledge only for peaceful purposes.
In talks in Geneva on October 1, he indicated that he would resume dialogue on the reduction of its nuclear programme, and a substantial part of its enriched uranium in exchange for fuel desperately needed for a medical research reactor.
The administration has pushed for such an agreement, as a way to build confidence between the two parties and to win time for negotiations.
But Since then, Iran appears to have moved from the tentative agreements, in part, say experts, because the Iranian leadership is divided on the possibility of engaging with the United States.
Frankly, the international community in relation to some of the proposals, which they had agreed in early October, has joined the international community, including the Russians and the Chinese, in terms of significant additional sanctions against the Iranians, said Gates.
President Obama has set a December 31 deadline for Iran to respond to the proposals, before he other options, including the continuation of what the Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton, once called " devastating sanctions. "
In a statement in New York, the mission of Iran to the United Nations has denounced what it called " baseless allegations " of some members of the Security Council on Iran's nuclear activities and said that willing to continue talks with the United States and five other world powers, " in order to achieve an appropriate solution in the long term. "
Gates, who was to return to Washington late on Friday, met in the morning with Iraqi Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki, before flying to the oil rich Kurdish region in Iraq to meetings with troops in Kirkuk and Kurdish officials in Irbil.
Tensions remain high between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq, in particular with regard to the borders, property rights and the distribution of revenues.
Gates urged both sides to reduce the potential for conflict, in order to avoid any delay in the U. S. plans to reduce the number of American troops 115,000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
Gates also sought to ease the Kurdish concern about the imminent withdrawal of troops. The American authorities have quoted Gates saying to Massoud Barzani, president of the Kurdistan regional government: " We will your security, prosperity and your autonomy within a unified Iraq.
We will not leave you. "
In China, a change of direction
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters on them, the the mother Earth is too tired to accommodate more children " and " a baby means one more tomb. "
Learned the lesson so well that, when government officials in Shanghai, alarmed by the low birth rate and the ageing population of their city, have radically changed direction this summer and began to encourage young couples to have more of a child, her response was instant and firm: never.
We have already given all our time and energy only for a child.
There is nothing for a second, said Wang, 31, a director of human resources with a son of 8 months.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one - child policy in China, creating two generations of children notoriously with good cheeks and spoiled, dubbed " little emperors ", a population crisis in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple, compared to six when the policy was implemented.
The distribution of the population, while it is anticipated that the number of residents aged 60 years and over, 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050. This is well above the global average of around 20 percent.
The imbalance is worse in the rich coastal cities with a highly educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for almost 22 percent of the population of residents registered in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission has said that fertile couples must have babies to help to reduce the proportion of the ageing population and to prevent a lack of manpower in the future ".
Shanghai is about to be " as old - but not so rich, however - that developed countries such as Japan and Sweden, " she said.
A gradual relief
Written in the constitution of the country in 1978, China's one - child policy is perhaps the most controversial mandate introduced by the Communist Party.
Couples who violate the policy face huge fines, up to three times their annual salary in some areas, and with discrimination in the workplace.
The Chinese authorities have attributed to the police on duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights activists have denounced abuses in the implementation of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced women pregnant with a second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have had geschlechtsselektive abortions, which unnatural ratio of men to women.
In recent years, the authorities of the population have gradually softened their position on the one - child policy.
In 2004, they have allowed more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife are children, and in 2007, many of their hard - line slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said that the central government recently even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one partner is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
In no time, posters encouraging families to have only one child, have been replaced by copies of regulations detailing who has the right to have a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city administration has sent to family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples in their home and slip leaflets under doors.
It has also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
The head of family planning officials say that the response has been disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for couples who want a second child after the launch of the campaign, the more urban districts reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five requests per month.
The disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city, in 2010 only slightly higher than 2009, but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning Committee of the municipality Caolu in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to give the best to their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and are legally permitted.
But like many Chinese, they have only the minimum health insurance and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West assess the one child policy ' as a matter of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
Yes, we are stealing the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not only the law.
Is money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their reluctance.
Wang, the manager of human resources, said that he wants a single child because she was: " We were the centre of the family and that everyone around us.
We are not accustomed to care for others and we do not really want to care of others. "
Chen Zijian, 42 years and owner of a translation company said it more bluntly.
For parents with two careers, middle class, reducing the birth rate, he said, is to have enough success to be selfish.
The people of 20 or 30 years grew up watching their parents struggle in during the early days of the Chinese capitalism and do not want to have this kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child requires a lot of time of his parents, he said.
A mother must abandon at least two years of their social life.
Then there are the problems of space, " we must modify its housing " - and the " if the child is 9 months old, we have a CV for the best nursery. "
Most of his friends are ready to face this once, said Chen, but not two.
Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living, he said.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
UN group plan to reduce emissions
The climate conference sponsored by the UN, characterised so far by offensive positions and mutual recriminations, a renewed focus on Friday with the publication of a document that provides for ambitious cuts in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations supporting most of the burden in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations that lack of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Prepared by a special working group of the UN, the text does not talk about how much money would give the rich countries to poor countries to tackle global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a range of options for the key issues, including how the developed economies and major emerging economies could reduce their production of carbon and what would be the upper limit of the global rise in temperature that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives a great deal of flexibility in the process, said John Coequyt, senior representatives of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has written six pages of the document, has put together a negotiating text of 180 pages to focus on what the Secretary - General executive on climate change, Yvo de Boer, described as " the big picture. "
It shows the outline of a possible agreement, in which the industrial nations together their emissions by 2020 to 25 to 45 percent, compared with 1990 levels, while major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce their 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years, to help the poorer countries to adapt to the impact of climate change - from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
The U. S. climate envoy Todd Stern has rejected, the mandatory reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared with voluntary reductions from the major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, with regard to what the Bush administration two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions of major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text does not enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei, stating that the US chief negotiator, lacked " common sense ", was " highly irresponsible " for having said earlier in the week that the United States would not help China to tackle global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the world's major powers are at stake, the fault lines both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more to the rescue of individual economies that to save the planet, with China and the United States on their respective obligations, while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder steps.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even if the vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in their attempt to make the major emitters accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game where is developing a new economic hegemony, said Ulate, who is also a regional adviser on climate change in Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change, said that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the key participants say that the talks will lead to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, has drafted a proposal for a treaty of 24 pages, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge - Metzger, head of the international climate unit of the European Commission, said that the action of the small island states has " political pressure on the political process, " in part because they are now unified and the emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks got a new urgency, as the delegates focused on the fact that they should solve most of the issues before the heads of government come to an agreement.
High - level officials, such as the Indian environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister, fell from their aircraft and rushed into the corridors of the Bella Center to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences, in order to " during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where every day 13,000 people come in and out of the convention centre, gitarrespielende activists hold late - night comedy shows, they make fun of the countries who betrayed and that proposals are drafted and distributed on paper rather than by e mail - is a challenge.
The intensity only built: almost all key ministers are now here and on Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice - president for global policy of Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
In Britain, the first train to 225 km/h will redefine the Monday
5h13, Monday morning, a whistle the darkness to point start of a train that will mark a revolution in transport in Britain.
The first high - speed commuter train in the country will reach 225 km/h, when as a bolt from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Transport Minister, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes aboard the first commuter train Javelin outside London.
He hopes that the new service linking Britain to an international network of fast trains and reliable and the large conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The neglected remote areas would become prosperous suburbs, the times of business travel will be and the exchange of plane and car on the national carbon emissions and would reduce the congestion on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties believe in this vision.
But the tens of billions of pounds needed to build a new rail network, the inevitable planning battle and fears about environmental damage the high - speed lines.
High Speed Two (HS2) , a company created in January to provide the government a feasibility study, Lord Adonis, According to the Times report on 30 December.
This will provide a detailed road map of the next stage for the high - speed network.
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be drawn within a radius of five metres in urban areas and areas where the impact on the environment can be controversial.
In the campaign, the plan will be fleshed out within a radius of 25 metres from the final route.
It is also expected that HS2 presents three options for a high - speed network to the north.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
The preferred option is being proposed is a configuration with and in which a high - speed line will go to the West Midlands.
The line would split in or near Birmingham, with a branch to the west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another in the north - east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would come to Scotland.
" It seems that this will be the most effective option, " said a member of the railways.
When completed, the journey time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first part, which will not open before 2025, would allow passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared with the little more than an hour today.
The proposals would allow trains to travel to 400km/h, making the British network the fastest in the world.
The initial route is designed to allow trains to long and capable of carrying 1,100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour could operate on a line in London - Birmingham.
A terminal can accommodate 20,000 passengers per hour would be necessary.
Given the constraints of space, it is expected that an existing station will be expanded to accommodate the high - speed network.
The railway industry experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he believes that the scheme should be put in place, but broad public consultation and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be made until after a general election.
Even if it launches the machine, the network would have to be built in sections.
The trains had to switch from the high - speed lines to existing rail lines in the north of Birmingham, maintaining journey times between London and Scotland over the three hours.
This is seen as a key sticking point needed to ensure a change of planes to trains, a reference point for the rail revolution.
