A panel of Roman sarcophagus that belonged to the French writer Emile Zola was sold on Thursday at $1.5 million, well above the estimated price, announced the art dealer Sotheby's.
This panel of 2 metres long by 63 cm high, dates from the third century after Christ, was estimated between 150,000 and 250,000 dollars.
The marble, representing four scenes in a sophisticated architectural framework, surrounded by sátiros and women, is a rare piece, there are only four or five in the world, " said Florent Heintz, Vice - President of the auction of art of ancient Rome and Egypt at Sotheby's.
It was sold between a hundred lots.
The sale runs, but this is certainly what the buyer, until now, most of it, " says the AFP a spokesman for Sotheby's, Dan Abernethy.
The discovery of the acquisition of marble by Emile Zola back in a few days.
