Drivers: three marathon for an agreement that the supply of Christmas
After three sessions of negotiations marathon, the trade unions in the streets, and only employers ' organisation to be stayed until the end, arrived Friday night to an agreement that puts an end to the strike and the threat on the supply of Christmas.
At the meeting of signatures on Friday evening, the secretary of state for transport, Dominique Bussereau, was " pleased " with the agreement, after several sessions of negotiations, which began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators were left in the morning Friday, with the hope of quickly to sign the agreement at the end of the morning.
And Even if three employers ' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But a meeting of more than six hours that began at 11 H was necessary to reach an agreement and the text is firm signed.
The conflict " would have been very damaging for business " and " it was feared that disrupt the festivities end of the year, " said Mr Bussereau.
The text provides for a wage increase of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport) , and 2.9% for the highest (international transport) .
The hourly rate for workers with the lowest wages rising from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros.
It is not much, but it is very far, explained Patrice Clos (FO) .
If so, we are going to give the order to our militants that there are no more cuts or blockages in the centres of supply.
But there can always be some who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of the TLF, acknowledged that it is " a good agreement ", although it was " difficult to give these wage increases in the face of international competition ".
According to him, the increases will be in the order of 170 euros per month for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is the agreement of common sense and respect for the employees, " said Maxime Dumont (CFDT) , while Thierry Douine (CFTC) spoke of " a historic agreement ".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) is " an acceptable compromise. "
The agreement also provides for the upgrading of travel expenses of 3% and the holding of general assemblies of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will address the issue of a 13th month and modernisation of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau recalled that " a decrease of EUR 100 million in employers ' was the subject of an amendment to the bill of the government the corrected finances for 2009, voted in the night from Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote " an identical ".
The signing of the TLF allows that the agreement, for the first of this organisation affiliated companies, and, secondly, to the entire profession, in the event an extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be " as quickly as possible, " assured Mr Bussereau.
The opposition of employers ' organisations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a " fool ", because the 100 million euro " had already been promised to the sector to offset part of the carbon tax. "
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate in an emergency, not as a shared analysis, but not to those who want to eat in the next Christmas Eve, laments the Unostra.
For the Otre, the agreement puts at risk " the stability of many SMEs in the sector over the next 12 months. "
