The promise of FonPeek
Peek is extremely limited, a device that serves only to look at the mail, without even able to see some kind of Deputy or surf the Internet.
Enjoyed his five minutes of fame in the United States, when Time magazine as one of the products of the year.
In truth, it is more difficult to see in the streets, but the idea is interesting, especially for young people.
Unlike the smartphones, Peek has a very low price and a very low, less than half of what it costs, for example, the subscription data of the iPhone.
Given its success, the company has launched two new devices: one designed exclusively for Twitter, the other with a free service data for life, for six times more expensive than the Peek.
Fonpeek, presented yesterday at the event, is the European version of the invention and its third incarnation.
It is equally limited as his American counterpart, but comes with a surprise.
The price of monthly maintenance, approximately 12 euros per month, includes the roaming across Europe.
Those who travel with a Smartphone already know what it is like to have to give up the data when it crosses the border or seek desperately a cafeteria with WiFi (or a connection of Fon) to be able to consult the mail.
The idea of a roaming at a fixed price is incredibly attractive and should in fact be possible for a long time.
Yes, some operators have special agreements and travel plans, but in my experience takes a doctorate in physics to understand and good glasses to read the small print.
The repeated criticism from the European Commission in relation to affordable roaming tariffs for the whole of Europe hardly have had a noticeable effect.
Outside the country of origin are afraid to use the data, and rightly so.
That A small device such as FonPeek (and it is always amazing that it has the name of Fon, although it has no WiFi) offers this type of tariffs, means that operators are starting to think differently and their data network.
Kindle is another good example, it includes the downloading of books and other research on the Internet.
Without Vetrag and without snags.
It is a device connected and pay for it at the time of purchase, and not every month.
And that is what I hope to see one day with FonPeek, an option to purchase with access to life as Peek already in the United States.
Not because I will to buy it.
I watch my mail on my phone, thank you.
I hope so because I believe that it is a fairer model for the consumer.
It would be interesting to see a computer with the same system.
