Acciona dispute its first motorway in Australia to Hochtief and Bouygues
Acciona fights for his first motorway in concession in Australia, market in which already works as a company manager of energy and water.
The site at stake is a tunnel valued at 1.7 billion Australian dollars (about 1.047 billion euros) .
The French company Bouygues and the German company Hochtief are its competitors.
A tunnel of 5 km long in the Australian city of Brisbane, on the east coast, has become the option closer to allow Acciona to settle in the country as a construction company and of motorways.
The city of the city wants to have by the end of 2014.
After opting for the public - private partnership (PPP) to complete the project, in a business plan under the tutelage of Erns& Young, the administration already has a list of finalists who will be responsible for the construction and operation of the toll.
In anticipation of their bids next May, the planned investment amounts to 1.7 billion Australian dollars (1.047 billion euros) and in the last phase three consortia, with a significant presence of European manufacturers.
The group called Transcity is led by Acciona, only Spanish company in smooth, and his associates are BMD and Ghella.
The first is one of the largest Australian, while the second, based in Italy, is one of the largest European specialists in underground works.
Against the team of Acciona enters the consortium Northern direct, with the presence of the British companies Laing O'Rourke, manager of the Australian infrastructure and the French manufacturer group Bouygues.
The third and final consortium that has passed the screening is LBRJV, whose capital is shared between the Australian Leighton (a subsidiary of the German builder Hochtief, which has in turn by ACS) , another local company, Baulderstone (owned by the German group Bilfinger Berger) and the Welsh company specializing in public works, Razel.
The Australian market infrastructure promises major projects and privatisation, but carries a clear difficulty of entry if not through the acquisition of a local construction company.
A strategy that have followed the companies Hochtief or Bilfinger, in addition to their Asian references, and issue for the Spanish giants of the sector.
Barely ACS has achieved a position in this market through its 30 per cent stake in Hochtief, owner of the aforementioned Leighton.
Assets millionaires
Acciona a geographical area of the utmost importance for the sector, on which it already has a large presence through its activity of energy supplier and in the desalination.
Among other assets, it has the largest wind park, Waubra (192 MW) in Victoria, and leads the group of companies to build and manage the dessalinisateur of Adelaide, with a budget of 700 million.
His intention now is to consolidate these two areas and take advantage of synergies to enter the fields of construction and operation of infrastructure.
The underground toll, promoted by the Office of the infrastructure of the city of Brisbane and the Northern Link (North) , is called to join the motorway west of Toowong with the bypass in Kelvin Grove (see map) over 5 km tunnel. It is the biggest measure to reduce traffic congestion in Brisbane.
The timetable set by the administration sets the award for the summer of 2010 and the start of construction work in December next year.
Despite the fact that this toll road will be open to traffic in recent months of 2014, it is not anticipated that the work will continue until 2016.
The tunnel began to be designed in 2005.
It will include two lanes for sense, an electronic toll system and a complex ventilation system.
The government of Queensland will provide 500 million Australian dollars (308 million euros) for its funding.
